n! Winning margin (points)\n|-\n| 2017\n| -\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[Glaschu Gaels]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[D\u00fanedin Connolly]] \n|-\n| 2014\n| [[D\u00fanedin Connolly]] \n|-\n|}\n\n===Junior Championship===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Year'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Winner'''\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Glaschu Gaels]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Glaschu Gaels]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[Glaschu Gaels]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Sands McSwiney]] \n|-\n|}\n\n===Homegrown Championship===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Year'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Winner'''\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[T\u00edr Conaill Harps]] \n|-\n| 2018\n| [[T\u00edr Conaill Harps]] \n|-\n| 2017\n| Not Competed\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[T\u00edr Conaill Harps]] \n|-\n| 2015\n| Not Competed\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[T\u00edr Conaill Harps]] \n|-\n|}\n\n==Inter-county team==\nScotland fields a representative county team in the All-Britain Junior Football Championship. 2014 was a breakthrough year for the team as they lifted the All-Britain Junior title for the first time. The team had only ever made the final once before back in 2006, but lost the final, in extra-time, to [[Warwickshire GAA|Warwickshire]]. On the way to the title they beat [[YorkshireGAA|Yorkshire]] and [[KilkennyGAA|Kilkenny]] before beating [[Warwickshire GAA|Warwickshire]] in the final to a scoreline of 3-10 to 2-07.\nThis set up an All-Ireland Junior Semi-final with [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]]. However they were defeated on the day to a scoreline of 1-17 to 0-06. Most recently the Scotland Men won the All-Britain title in 2019 against a tough Warwickshire team. They went on to contest the All-Ireland Quarter Final versus [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]].\n\n\n2015 became a momentous year for the Scotland ladies team as they reached the All-Ireland Junior Final to be played at Croke Park. They beat [[Derry GAA|Derry]] with a score line of 1-13 to 2-05 at Fingallians GAA ground. They played a tough game against [[Louth GAA|Louth]] at Croke Park on 27 September 2015. The\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Scottish Sport}}\n{{Gaelic games in Britain}}\n{{GAA bodies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scotland Gaa}}\n[[Category:Scotland GAA| ]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in Scotland|GAA]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games governing bodies in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Sport in Scotland]]\n\n{{GAA-stub}}\n{{Scotland-sport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox GAA county |\n county gaa = Scotland GAA|\n crest           = [[File:Scotland GAA logo.jpg|150px]] |\n irish = Albain  |\n province = [[Britain GAA|Britain]] |\n grounds = Clydebank Community Sport Hub, \n60 Dean Street, Clydebank \nG81 1RL|\n dominant sport = Gaelic football |\n pattern_la=_shoulder_stripes_white_stripes_alt|pattern_b=_collarwhite_horizontalwhite |pattern_ra=_shoulder_stripes_white_stripes_alt|pattern_so1 = __3_stripes_white|\n leftarm=182D69|body=182D69|rightarm=182D69 |shorts=|socks=182D69 |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsfile.com/id/RP0061864/|title=Sportsfile - Ireland v Scotland - Senior Men's Shinty International - RP0061864|first=|last=Sportsfile|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n|}}\nThe Scotland Board of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) or '''Scotland GAA''' ({{Lang-gd|Comann L\u00f9th-chleasach G\u00e0idheal na h-Alba}}) is one of the [[GAA county|county boards]] of the GAA outside Ireland, and is responsible for [[Gaelic games]] in Scotland. The county board is also responsible for the Scottish inter-county teams. The Board participates with [[London GAA|London]], [[Gloucestershire GAA|Gloucestershire]], [[Hertfordshire GAA|Hertfordshire]], [[Lancashire GAA|Lancashire]], [[Warwickshire GAA|Warwickshire]], and [[Yorkshire GAA|Yorkshire]] under the [[British GAA]].\n\n==List of Clubs==\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef\"\n!Club\n!Colours\n!City\n|-\n|[[D\u00